default&#xa0;default3.1 In spite of the difficulties of applying one set of principles to suc
defaulth an obviously diverse sector, 
defaultACEVO recommends cer
defaulttain good practices when it comes to setting Chief Executive Pay. 
default3.2 Charity pay at director level and above is the responsibility of the Board of Trustees, 
defaultwhose decision-mak
defaulting will be overseen
default by the Chair
default. In large charities the Trustees will often 
defaultdelegate the s
defaultetting of executive pay to a Remuneration
default Sub-Committee, which decides executive salaries and pension schemes. 
defaultIt might
default also review the responsibili
defaultty for 
defaultsetting other staff pay, 
defaultor delegate it
default to the appropriate Finance or Human Resources d
defaultirector.
default3.3 Many large charities also use recruitment consultants to assist with recruiting senior executives. Together with the charity’s Board of Trustees, consultants will usually set pay after considering organisation turnover, number of employees, in
default-job risk, pay of other directors and the possible use of performance-related incentives. Pay levels may also reflect the need to retain employees who may consider jobs in other related sectors. For example, international agencies such as the UN can of
defaultfer 
defaultdirector pay of at least £80
default,000, so 
defaultlarge international aid charities such as Oxfam, British Red Cross and Save the Children (all of which pay their CEOs over £100,000) need to keep their pay competitive to attract and retain the best leadership. Pay is o
defaultften set according to the dictates of the organisation and the job market in the sector, just as would happen in any other industry. Boards often also consider average senior pay in other comparable sectors, such as:
default&#xa0;
default3.4 ACEVO recognises that th
defaultere may not be sufficient publ
defaultic
defaultly-available guidance on the considerations that trustees make when setting executive pay. This is why 
defaultare working
default to publicise
default five principles of best practice for the charity sector when setting pay for employees. These principles ensure value for money for beneficiaries, staff, 
defaultfunder
defaults and the 
defaultpublic purse
default.  They are: transparency, proportionality, performance, retention and pr
defaultotocol.
default3.5 These principles are appropriate to charities of all sizes. In larger charities where trustees are more distant from the day-to-day running of the organisation, they may delegate control over pay to a Remuneration Committee. Its terms of refere
defaultnce would be formally approved by a vote of the trustees, and control over pay of other 
defaultemployees
default delegated to a Finance or Human Resources Director. Charity Commission Document CC8, section D7 briefly outlines the Commission’s good practice guidance for c
defaultontrol, by trustees, over wages and salaries.
default A
defaultCEVO
default recommends this practice for larger charities and recommends that the principles of good pay apply to the work of remuneration committees.
